. By exploring what were actually the mainstream ideologies and cultural practices of the period, the authors argue that the postwar consensus was itself a precarious cultural ideal that was characterized by internal tensions and, while containing elements of conservatism, reflected considerable diversity in the way in which citizenship identities were defined. Contributors include Denyse Baillargeon (Université de Montréal), P.E. Bryden (Mount Allison University), Nancy Christie, Michael Gauvreau, Karine Hebert (Carleton University), Len Kuffert (Carleton University), and Peter S. McInnis (St Francis Xavier University).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh1 aBaillargeon, Denyse, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBryden, P.E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristie, Nancy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGauvreau, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aGauvreau, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHébert, Karine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKuffert, Leonard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcinnis, Peter S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077357144040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773571440423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773571440/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrad